5
00:00:11,260 --> 00:00:15,400
going to present results of
a study on the role of fusion

6
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:18,680
in a decarbonized
electricity system.

7
00:00:18,680 --> 00:00:23,100
The full report for the study
is being released today.

8
00:00:23,100 --> 00:00:25,500
This study was done
by the MIT Energy

9
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:30,000
Initiative in collaboration with
MIT's Plasma Science and Fusion

10
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:32,940
Center, and involved the
research and analysis

11
00:00:32,940 --> 00:00:37,050
of an interdisciplinary team
of more than 30 researchers,

12
00:00:37,050 --> 00:00:40,770
with expertise ranging from
nuclear science and engineering,

13
00:00:40,770 --> 00:00:43,920
to economics and policy.

14
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:46,500
Fusion has long
captured the imagination

15
00:00:46,500 --> 00:00:50,225
of those interested in
emissions-free, abundant energy.

16
00:00:50,225 --> 00:00:53,390

17
00:00:53,390 --> 00:00:57,230
With more than 40 fusion startup
companies and more than 100

18
00:00:57,230 --> 00:01:00,000
government-supported
fusion projects,

19
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,780
there has never been more
momentum and enthusiasm

20
00:01:02,780 --> 00:01:07,680
for the role of fusion
in the energy transition.

21
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:10,050
Two characteristics
make fusion particularly

22
00:01:10,050 --> 00:01:12,480
important to the
energy transition.

23
00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:17,130
First, that it can provide
zero carbon firm power.

24
00:01:17,130 --> 00:01:20,870
This is not only essential to
the future electricity system,

25
00:01:20,870 --> 00:01:24,800
there simply are not many
options for providing it.

26
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:27,770
Second, fusion can
also meet needs

27
00:01:27,770 --> 00:01:31,990
for scalable energy-dense
generation capacity.

28
00:01:31,990 --> 00:01:33,880
So the time is
right to understand

29
00:01:33,880 --> 00:01:38,350
how fusion power could
transform electricity generation

30
00:01:38,350 --> 00:01:41,056
in the decades ahead.

31
00:01:41,056 --> 00:01:43,430
Among the questions we
addressed in this study

32
00:01:43,430 --> 00:01:46,610
are how fusion will
complement and coexist

33
00:01:46,610 --> 00:01:50,450
with other low-carbon energy
technologies, deployment

34
00:01:50,450 --> 00:01:55,760
scale and global distribution,
sensitivity to costs,

35
00:01:55,760 --> 00:01:58,400
sensitivity to
emissions constraints,

36
00:01:58,400 --> 00:02:01,340
sensitivity to
renewable resources,

37
00:02:01,340 --> 00:02:04,880
and critical materials
and supply chains.

38
00:02:04,880 --> 00:02:08,419
Not only can this understanding
be helpful to strategic planners

39
00:02:08,419 --> 00:02:10,850
and policy-makers,
but it can also

40
00:02:10,850 --> 00:02:14,720
be helpful to those involved
in fusion commercialization,

41
00:02:14,720 --> 00:02:18,320
because it provides economic
targets for the use of fusion

42
00:02:18,320 --> 00:02:20,420
in electricity markets.

43
00:02:20,420 --> 00:02:23,390
This better quantifies the
technical design challenges

44
00:02:23,390 --> 00:02:25,760
for fusion developers
with respect

45
00:02:25,760 --> 00:02:29,940
to pricing, availability,
and load following.

