49
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:42,690
Randy?

50
00:02:42,690 --> 00:02:45,540
Thank you very much,
Professor Armstrong.

51
00:02:45,540 --> 00:02:49,060
And thank you all for
attending the webinar today.

52
00:02:49,060 --> 00:02:51,850
Before discussing
the fusion study,

53
00:02:51,850 --> 00:02:55,110
I'm going to take a very
brief moment to give you

54
00:02:55,110 --> 00:02:56,420
an overview of fusion.

55
00:02:56,420 --> 00:03:14,630

56
00:03:14,630 --> 00:03:19,100
When two nuclei
fuse together, they

57
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:21,360
release a tremendous
amount of energy,

58
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:25,280
more than a million times the
energy released per unit mass

59
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:27,560
from combusting of fossil fuels.

60
00:03:27,560 --> 00:03:31,860
And this energy source does
not release greenhouse gases.

61
00:03:31,860 --> 00:03:35,540
Thus, fusion has great
potential as a energy

62
00:03:35,540 --> 00:03:36,980
source going forward.

63
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:42,150
However, to enable fusion
to occur at a useful scale,

64
00:03:42,150 --> 00:03:44,660
we need very high
temperatures, and we

65
00:03:44,660 --> 00:03:47,750
must bring the
fusion fuels together

66
00:03:47,750 --> 00:03:51,420
via confinement to
enable them to fuse.

67
00:03:51,420 --> 00:03:57,020
There are various categories
of confinement methods.

68
00:03:57,020 --> 00:03:59,640
One method is
magnetic confinement,

69
00:03:59,640 --> 00:04:01,940
where a very strong
magnetic field

70
00:04:01,940 --> 00:04:06,920
is used to ensure the fuel ions
are kept close together and away

71
00:04:06,920 --> 00:04:10,160
from the walls of the reactor.

72
00:04:10,160 --> 00:04:13,050
Another method is
inertial confinement,

73
00:04:13,050 --> 00:04:16,170
where lasers or
projectiles are used

74
00:04:16,170 --> 00:04:22,350
to rapidly compress and
heat up the fuel capsule.

75
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:25,150
A third method is magneto
inertial confinement,

76
00:04:25,150 --> 00:04:30,080
which uses a combination of the
prior two confinement methods.

77
00:04:30,080 --> 00:04:33,200
These confinement methods have
been successfully demonstrated

78
00:04:33,200 --> 00:04:36,980
in experiments, and
fusion has been achieved.

79
00:04:36,980 --> 00:04:42,170
However, the challenge is in
the engineering and economics.

80
00:04:42,170 --> 00:04:44,570
Commercial success
for fusion energy

81
00:04:44,570 --> 00:04:47,990
requires that we build
economically-viable systems

82
00:04:47,990 --> 00:04:51,260
to handle the high temperatures
and the high-energy particles

83
00:04:51,260 --> 00:04:53,900
that are released,
and also, the ability

84
00:04:53,900 --> 00:04:59,060
to convert the released
energy into electricity.

85
00:04:59,060 --> 00:05:02,960
Each fuel type and
confinement method

86
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:05,450
has its own set of
engineering challenges

87
00:05:05,450 --> 00:05:07,966
and its own
innovative solutions.

88
00:05:07,966 --> 00:05:14,150

89
00:05:14,150 --> 00:05:17,390
As Professor Armstrong stated,
given the great potential

90
00:05:17,390 --> 00:05:20,300
for fusion, it deserves
a close examination

91
00:05:20,300 --> 00:05:23,510
to understand how fusion
power plants could

92
00:05:23,510 --> 00:05:28,970
transform the energy generation
in the decades ahead.

93
00:05:28,970 --> 00:05:33,530
We started this project
in fall of 2022,

94
00:05:33,530 --> 00:05:38,550
and we organized the analysis
along four major work streams.

95
00:05:38,550 --> 00:05:42,590
These were examine the global
deployment of fusion power

96
00:05:42,590 --> 00:05:44,300
plants in all
regions of the world

97
00:05:44,300 --> 00:05:46,670
out to the end of the century.

98
00:05:46,670 --> 00:05:51,710
We also analyzed the
subregional grid at grid scale

99
00:05:51,710 --> 00:05:56,480
to understand how fusion will
fit in with the generation mix

100
00:05:56,480 --> 00:06:00,610
when you have different
resources available.

101
00:06:00,610 --> 00:06:02,740
We also assessed
critical materials

102
00:06:02,740 --> 00:06:06,130
and manufactured components
that are needed for fusion

103
00:06:06,130 --> 00:06:08,230
to understand
potential bottlenecks

104
00:06:08,230 --> 00:06:13,910
and to build out the fleet
of fusion power plants.

105
00:06:13,910 --> 00:06:17,960
We also examined
key cost-drivers

106
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:20,950
for fusion power plants.

107
00:06:20,950 --> 00:06:23,170
I also want to take
a moment to point out

108
00:06:23,170 --> 00:06:26,530
that this study intentionally
does not make predictions

109
00:06:26,530 --> 00:06:29,200
about when fusion will
be deployed commercially,

110
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:33,440
or which fusion technology will
come first, or which fusion--

111
00:06:33,440 --> 00:06:36,990
or what will be the cost
of fusion in the future.

112
00:06:36,990 --> 00:06:40,600
Instead, we have conducted
a scenario analysis

113
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,790
and sensitivity
analysis in order

114
00:06:42,790 --> 00:06:46,930
to focus on the conditions
required for fusion

115
00:06:46,930 --> 00:06:48,540
to be deployed at scale.

116
00:06:48,540 --> 00:06:52,620

117
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:58,620
Now we will move on
to the main findings

118
00:06:58,620 --> 00:07:01,560
from the study with a
series of presentations

119
00:07:01,560 --> 00:07:04,780
by several members
of the project team.

120
00:07:04,780 --> 00:07:07,650
And I will be starting
with Sergey Paltsev, who

121
00:07:07,650 --> 00:07:11,290
led the global analysis
workstream for the study.

122
00:07:11,290 --> 00:07:14,970
Sergey is an economist, and
he is the deputy director

123
00:07:14,970 --> 00:07:17,970
for the MIT Center for
Sustainability, Science,

124
00:07:17,970 --> 00:07:21,960
and Strategy, and he is also
a senior research scientist

125
00:07:21,960 --> 00:07:25,170
for the MIT Energy Initiative.

126
00:07:25,170 --> 00:07:26,840
Sergey?

127
00:07:26,840 --> 00:07:28,760
