128
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:31,640
Stressed in the
earlier remarks, there

129
00:07:31,640 --> 00:07:35,330
are substantial uncertainties
about several aspects

130
00:07:35,330 --> 00:07:38,150
on the technological
side of energy.

131
00:07:38,150 --> 00:07:41,720
On the economic side, one
of the goals of this study

132
00:07:41,720 --> 00:07:44,060
is to provide to
technology developers

133
00:07:44,060 --> 00:07:48,800
the indicators of the goals
for the potential economic case

134
00:07:48,800 --> 00:07:50,420
for fusion energy.

135
00:07:50,420 --> 00:07:54,180
To better understand
these indicators,

136
00:07:54,180 --> 00:07:56,720
we assess several scenarios.

137
00:07:56,720 --> 00:07:59,280
Details of the scenarios
are provided in the report,

138
00:07:59,280 --> 00:08:01,310
but let me very
briefly orient you

139
00:08:01,310 --> 00:08:04,110
about the major settings
of these scenarios.

140
00:08:04,110 --> 00:08:08,810
First, we assessed the
world, which is on its path

141
00:08:08,810 --> 00:08:10,890
to decarbonization goals.

142
00:08:10,890 --> 00:08:14,510
And in all scenarios, the
world reaches the goal

143
00:08:14,510 --> 00:08:17,888
of stabilizing the global
temperature at 1.5 degrees

144
00:08:17,888 --> 00:08:18,980
Celcius.

145
00:08:18,980 --> 00:08:23,700
In these scenarios, we do not
force any particular technology,

146
00:08:23,700 --> 00:08:29,250
but rather, they compete based
on their relative economic

147
00:08:29,250 --> 00:08:30,540
competitiveness.

148
00:08:30,540 --> 00:08:34,020
Second, we evaluated
several cases

149
00:08:34,020 --> 00:08:38,250
for the cost of zero carbon
dispatchable technology,

150
00:08:38,250 --> 00:08:42,330
like fusion, and we
evaluate the full dynamics

151
00:08:42,330 --> 00:08:44,590
of the costs over time.

152
00:08:44,590 --> 00:08:47,430
And for simplicity,
we label the cases

153
00:08:47,430 --> 00:08:52,610
for fusion in terms of their
overnight capital costs in 2050.

154
00:08:52,610 --> 00:08:56,760
So it means that before
2050, the costs are higher,

155
00:08:56,760 --> 00:09:00,120
and after 2050, the
costs are decreasing.

156
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:02,650
And the full curves are
provided in the report,

157
00:09:02,650 --> 00:09:07,200
but for simplicity, you will
see these labels, $8,000,

158
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:12,300
$5,600 per kilowatt, and
these are the costs for 2050.

159
00:09:12,300 --> 00:09:15,810
To assess the potential
societal value,

160
00:09:15,810 --> 00:09:19,260
we compared the scenarios
where the fusion does not

161
00:09:19,260 --> 00:09:22,950
exist with the
scenarios where fusion

162
00:09:22,950 --> 00:09:25,320
exists at different costs.

163
00:09:25,320 --> 00:09:32,220
So, for example, where fusion
exists at $8,000 per kilowatt,

164
00:09:32,220 --> 00:09:35,850
you can see, represented
in the blue line,

165
00:09:35,850 --> 00:09:39,910
the societal value
of the fusion.

166
00:09:39,910 --> 00:09:44,070
And, of course, if fusion
developers are able to reduce

167
00:09:44,070 --> 00:09:48,600
their costs, in this example,
to $5,600 per kilowatt,

168
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:52,240
the economic value
for society is higher.

169
00:09:52,240 --> 00:09:56,600
And that example is given by
the yellow line on this graph.

170
00:09:56,600 --> 00:09:58,680
We can also aggregate
those benefits

171
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:01,020
over time and over the century.

172
00:10:01,020 --> 00:10:03,490
Compared to a scenario
without fusion,

173
00:10:03,490 --> 00:10:10,080
the global cumulative GDP would
be 0.4% higher in our base case

174
00:10:10,080 --> 00:10:19,020
of $8,000, and if the costs
are lower, to $5,600, well,

175
00:10:19,020 --> 00:10:20,710
then the benefits are higher.

176
00:10:20,710 --> 00:10:24,450
In that particular case,
it's about 1% increase

177
00:10:24,450 --> 00:10:28,950
in the global GDP if fusion
energy enters the mix.

178
00:10:28,950 --> 00:10:31,620
So these results
indicate that investment

179
00:10:31,620 --> 00:10:34,380
in developing and
deployment of fusion energy

180
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:38,520
can create a large societal
value for the global economy

181
00:10:38,520 --> 00:10:42,090
and support the efforts to
achieve decarbonization goals

182
00:10:42,090 --> 00:10:43,813
over the course of the century.

183
00:10:43,813 --> 00:10:44,605
Next slide, please.

184
00:10:44,605 --> 00:10:48,600

185
00:10:48,600 --> 00:10:53,190
We also ask the
question, how large

186
00:10:53,190 --> 00:10:59,070
is the contribution of fusion
energy to the global power

187
00:10:59,070 --> 00:11:00,540
generation mix?

188
00:11:00,540 --> 00:11:03,730
And in this graph,
in these diagrams,

189
00:11:03,730 --> 00:11:07,320
in these four diagrams, you see
different cases for different

190
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:12,300
costs of the fusion, where the
value of the cost from less than

191
00:11:12,300 --> 00:11:17,390
$3,000 per kilowatt, to more
than $11,000 per kilowatt.

192
00:11:17,390 --> 00:11:21,360
And you can see the results
in this magenta color

193
00:11:21,360 --> 00:11:25,680
for fusion, that the share in
the global power generation mix

194
00:11:25,680 --> 00:11:29,970
varies from less than
10% to about half.

195
00:11:29,970 --> 00:11:34,530
And this show that the
contribution of fusion

196
00:11:34,530 --> 00:11:39,030
can be quite large, but this
sizeable deployment of fusion

197
00:11:39,030 --> 00:11:43,033
is going to be mostly in the
second half of the century.

198
00:11:43,033 --> 00:11:43,825
Next slide, please.

199
00:11:43,825 --> 00:11:47,570

200
00:11:47,570 --> 00:11:51,060
To realize these sizable
contributions of fusion,

201
00:11:51,060 --> 00:11:55,130
the technological, economic,
and regulatory challenges

202
00:11:55,130 --> 00:11:58,050
of fusion energy
needs to be addressed,

203
00:11:58,050 --> 00:12:00,530
and we need to start
addressing them now

204
00:12:00,530 --> 00:12:04,070
to have the meaningful
deployment by mid-century.

205
00:12:04,070 --> 00:12:06,330
As you can see from
these illustrations,

206
00:12:06,330 --> 00:12:10,010
we found that initial deployment
is strongest in the United

207
00:12:10,010 --> 00:12:11,650
States and Europe.

208
00:12:11,650 --> 00:12:15,880
The largest increase in
fusion takes place in India

209
00:12:15,880 --> 00:12:18,680
during the last three
decades of the century.

210
00:12:18,680 --> 00:12:21,170
And Africa is a late
adopter of fusion,

211
00:12:21,170 --> 00:12:25,190
but seeing very strong growth
in the late of the century.

212
00:12:25,190 --> 00:12:29,720
We also stress that these
results depend on many factors,

213
00:12:29,720 --> 00:12:32,440
and some of them are
listed on this slide.

214
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:35,590
Of course, many aspects
of fusion operations

215
00:12:35,590 --> 00:12:38,990
are beyond the scope
of our global modeling,

216
00:12:38,990 --> 00:12:41,320
and therefore, the
exact numerical values

217
00:12:41,320 --> 00:12:44,800
should be treated with a
great degree of caution.

218
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:48,970
We provide some more granular
results in this next session

219
00:12:48,970 --> 00:12:50,390
and in the report.

220
00:12:50,390 --> 00:12:53,170
I want to finish my
part by emphasizing

221
00:12:53,170 --> 00:12:55,780
that with all
inherent uncertainty

222
00:12:55,780 --> 00:12:57,670
about the potential
cost reductions

223
00:12:57,670 --> 00:13:02,050
in technological options,
one message is very clear,

224
00:13:02,050 --> 00:13:05,410
the successful resolution
of technological challenges

225
00:13:05,410 --> 00:13:08,500
and appropriate
regulatory incentives.

226
00:13:08,500 --> 00:13:11,830
Fusion can provide a
substantial contribution

227
00:13:11,830 --> 00:13:16,070
to the world that requires
the expanding electrification.

228
00:13:16,070 --> 00:13:20,440
And it helps the global
society to reach and sustain

229
00:13:20,440 --> 00:13:22,700
its decarbonization goals.

