saw different roles of fusion
given the same constraints.

255
00:14:40,820 --> 00:14:44,440
We adopted two main metrics
to quantify fusion's role.

256
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:49,340
First, penetration, which just
measures what level of adoption

257
00:14:49,340 --> 00:14:51,530
we're seeing in
general in comparison

258
00:14:51,530 --> 00:14:54,140
to the national
average, and the second

259
00:14:54,140 --> 00:14:56,480
is sensitivity,
which measures how

260
00:14:56,480 --> 00:15:02,120
much fusion penetration changes
as we adjust our carbon ceiling.

261
00:15:02,120 --> 00:15:05,270
We've grouped together the
regions with similar fusion

262
00:15:05,270 --> 00:15:08,900
trends to better understand the
characteristics of those regions

263
00:15:08,900 --> 00:15:10,550
which affect fusion.

264
00:15:10,550 --> 00:15:13,610
I'll walk you through
this chart on the slide

265
00:15:13,610 --> 00:15:16,970
here which summarizes our
findings really well, starting

266
00:15:16,970 --> 00:15:19,220
on the left, with the
regions which saw the highest

267
00:15:19,220 --> 00:15:21,890
need for fusion, and then
moving to the ones which

268
00:15:21,890 --> 00:15:24,410
saw less need for fusion.

269
00:15:24,410 --> 00:15:27,410
So first, the
Atlantic and Southeast

270
00:15:27,410 --> 00:15:30,210
saw high penetration
and low sensitivity,

271
00:15:30,210 --> 00:15:33,920
meaning that they saw a large
amount of fusion present

272
00:15:33,920 --> 00:15:36,560
at all carbon caps
that we tested.

273
00:15:36,560 --> 00:15:40,070
This is because these regions
have very limited and weak

274
00:15:40,070 --> 00:15:43,100
onshore wind resources,
and also don't

275
00:15:43,100 --> 00:15:45,740
have any alternative
dispatchable low-carbon

276
00:15:45,740 --> 00:15:50,090
technologies, such as
hydro or geothermal.

277
00:15:50,090 --> 00:15:52,700
Next, we have California,
the Northeast,

278
00:15:52,700 --> 00:15:56,570
and the Southwest, which saw
moderate fusion adoption.

279
00:15:56,570 --> 00:16:01,200
We didn't see any fusion at 50
grams of CO2 per kilowatt hour,

280
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:04,550
but installations were
reaching up to 50% of demand

281
00:16:04,550 --> 00:16:07,910
at the deepest
decarbonization levels.

282
00:16:07,910 --> 00:16:11,240
These regions have moderate
onshore wind resources

283
00:16:11,240 --> 00:16:15,890
and decent low-carbon-supporting
technologies.

284
00:16:15,890 --> 00:16:19,520
The Northwest saw the
lowest penetration

285
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:21,620
and a low sensitivity
level, meaning

286
00:16:21,620 --> 00:16:24,800
we didn't see a lot
of fusion until we

287
00:16:24,800 --> 00:16:27,600
reached lower emissions caps.

288
00:16:27,600 --> 00:16:30,200
And even at those low
caps, the penetration

289
00:16:30,200 --> 00:16:32,360
did stay relatively low.

290
00:16:32,360 --> 00:16:36,230
This is because the Northwest
has decent wind resources

291
00:16:36,230 --> 00:16:39,320
and a large amount of
geothermal and hydro, which

292
00:16:39,320 --> 00:16:41,800
fusion is competing with.

293
00:16:41,800 --> 00:16:44,230
Lastly, we have the
Central, North Central,

294
00:16:44,230 --> 00:16:47,740
and Texas regions, which saw
low penetration, but high

295
00:16:47,740 --> 00:16:49,630
sensitivity.

296
00:16:49,630 --> 00:16:52,750
There was no fusion adoption
until deep decarbonization

297
00:16:52,750 --> 00:16:57,550
levels, but when fusion is
adopted, it reaches almost 50%

298
00:16:57,550 --> 00:17:00,210
of demand in some regions.

299
00:17:00,210 --> 00:17:02,670
These regions have the
strongest wind resources,

300
00:17:02,670 --> 00:17:05,940
but don't have any alternative
low-carbon-supporting

301
00:17:05,940 --> 00:17:07,980
technologies.

302
00:17:07,980 --> 00:17:10,920
This analysis summarizes
the driving factors

303
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:12,500
behind fusion adoption.

304
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:16,599
First and foremost, you need
decarbonization targets.

305
00:17:16,599 --> 00:17:20,220
Without carbon constraints, the
role of fusion is very limited.

306
00:17:20,220 --> 00:17:22,530
But fusion plays
an important role

307
00:17:22,530 --> 00:17:25,930
for all regions at deep
decarbonization targets,

308
00:17:25,930 --> 00:17:30,060
with installations reaching
at least 25% of demand

309
00:17:30,060 --> 00:17:33,370
in all regions at our deepest
decarbonization level,

310
00:17:33,370 --> 00:17:35,970
1 gram of CO2 per kilowatt hour.

311
00:17:35,970 --> 00:17:40,770
Secondly, fusion adoption
is dependent on your more

312
00:17:40,770 --> 00:17:46,350
conventional renewable
energy resources, wind,

313
00:17:46,350 --> 00:17:47,720
what are your capacity factors?

314
00:17:47,720 --> 00:17:48,970
What are your buildout limits?

315
00:17:48,970 --> 00:17:50,460
And then, also,
we know that it's

316
00:17:50,460 --> 00:17:54,340
competing with alternative
firm low-carbon technologies,

317
00:17:54,340 --> 00:17:56,290
your hydro and your geothermal.

318
00:17:56,290 --> 00:18:02,430

319
00:18:02,430 --> 00:18:05,110
Thank you very much, Amanda.

